1 Introduction to research

1.1 Initial expectations / biases

  • Not expecting significant seasonal trends, since cereal is a household staple
  • Less expensive cereals sell more, more expensive cereals sell less
  • More expensive cereals will sell more with promotions relative to without promotions

2 Load data and get initial summary

# Load sales data
sales_df <- read.csv("mtp_sales_data.csv")
# Load product data
product_df <- read.csv("mtp_product_data.csv")

3.3 Data Transformations

# Check if UPC in product_df is unique
sum(duplicated(product_df$UPC))
## [1] 0
# Key cleanup in sales_df: replace periods with dashes
sales_df$UPC <- str_replace_all(sales_df$UPC, "[.]", "-")
# Key cleanup in product_df: remove first three characters
product_df$UPC <- sub("00-", "", product_df$UPC)
# Left join with sales_df as left table to preserve all sales data
full_df <- left_join(sales_df, product_df, by = c("UPC", "UPC"))
# Check for any null values in joined df
sum(is.na(full_df)) # no null values
## [1] 0
# Rename iri_key variable for clarity
full_df <- rename(full_df, "store_key" = iri_key)
# Create new variables; 
full_df <- mutate(full_df, 
                  company = as.factor(
                    ifelse(str_detect(full_df$brand, "KELLOGGS"), "Kellogg",
                           ifelse(str_detect(full_df$brand, "GENERAL MILLS"), "General Mills", "Post"))),
                  total_sales = (units * price),
                  season = (week %/% 14) + 1,
                  ad2 = ifelse(ad == "NONE", 0, 1))
#Note above is integer division where 14 is number of weeks per season plus 1 so that week 13 is put in the first season (similar with week 52)
# The + 1 after the integer division is so seasons go 1 - 4 instead of 0 - 3

#realized also want total volumes too
full_df <- full_df %>% mutate(total_volume = units * volume)

Initial Observations

store_key

  • there are a large number of stores, so grouping by stores may not yield useful results

units

  • mean slightly higher than the mean with outliers, so skewed to the right
  • what are the total units sold by brand?

price

  • roughly symmetric distribution
  • majority of items (75%) are $4.39 or less, regardless of brand
  • max price of $9.99 indicates an outlier
  • Maybe useful to look at price/volume for a consistent comparable? Seems to be a wide variety of package sizes which leads to more variety in price/package

promo

  • majority of sold items (79%) do not have in-store promotions, so must be mindful of sample sizes

ad

  • majority of sold items (88.48%) dont have ads

volume

  • mean and median are about the same; use either as measure of central tendency
  • majority of items (75%) are 1.12 or less

flavor

  • regular and toasted are the top two flavors

package

  • 97.51% of observations come in a box

5.1.4 Sales by company and brand

# Sales volume and dollar amount by company
full_df %>%
  group_by(company) %>%
  summarise(units_sold = sum(units),
            p_units = sum(promo * units),
            percent_p_units = (round(p_units/units_sold,4)*100),
            total_sales = sum(total_sales),
            p_sales = sum(promo * units * price),
            percent_p_sales = round(p_sales/total_sales, 4)*100) %>%
  arrange(desc(percent_p_units))

7.1 Statistical tests

7.2 Test of promo impact to overall General Mills sales

  • Ho: GM avg sales w/out promo - GM avg sales w/promo = 0
  • Ha: GM avg sales w/out promo - GM avg sales w/promo != 0

Alpha = 0.025

# Set df to t for easier subsetting in t tests
t <- full_df

# Test for differences between promo and non-promo sales for General Mills
t.test(t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$promo == 0],
       t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$promo == 1],
       conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$promo == 0] and t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$promo == 1]
## t = -0.7662, df = 2115.6, p-value = 0.4436
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.9985901  0.8756323
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  35.60590  36.16737
  • We do not reject the null hypothesis
  • There is no statistically significant difference between promo and non-promo sales for General Mills

Conclusion: There is no statistical evidence to support that promos make a difference to sales for General Mills overall. However, I will test for differences within each brand.

7.4 General Mills brands, promo v no promo

Hypothesis test set-up for all GM brands:

  • Ho: Brand avg sales w/ promo - Brand avg sales w/out promo = 0
  • Ha: Brand avg sales w/ promo - Brand avg sales w/out promo != 0

Alpha = 0.025

# Test for Lucky Charms
(t1 <- t.test(t$total_sales[t$promo == 1 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS LUCKY CHARMS"],
             t$total_sales[t$promo == 0 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS LUCKY CHARMS"],
             conf.level = 0.95))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  t$total_sales[t$promo == 1 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS LUCKY CHARMS"] and t$total_sales[t$promo == 0 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS LUCKY CHARMS"]
## t = 2.9748, df = 476.11, p-value = 0.003081
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.545826 7.561649
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  39.91911  35.36537
  • reject the null hypothesis
  • there is a statistically significant difference between promo and non promo sales for Lucky Charms
  • On avg, promo sales are higher than non-promo sales
# Test for Kix
(t2 <- t.test(t$total_sales[t$promo == 1 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS KIX"],
             t$total_sales[t$promo == 0 & t$brand == "GENERAL MILLS KIX"],

7.6 Test for impact of ads on sales

  • Ho: GM avg sales w/ ads - GM avg sales w/out = 0
  • Ha: GM avg sales w/ ads - GM avg sales w/out ads != 0
# Test for differences between ad v no ad sales for General Mills
t.test(t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$ad2 == 1],
       t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$ad2 == 0],
       conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$ad2 == 1] and t$total_sales[t$company == "General Mills" & t$ad2 == 0]
## t = 1.1963, df = 920.69, p-value = 0.2319
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.7285194  3.0032385
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  36.73027  35.59291
  • We do not reject the null hypothesis
  • There is not statistically significant difference between the average sales of General Mills cereals that have ads versus the cereals that dont have ads

Conclusion: Ads do not make a consistent difference in overall sales for General Mills cereals. However, about 77% of the time we can expect to see impacts of ads that are either positive or negative for the company overall.

Based on the hypothesis tests above, we see that not every General Mills brand sees a positive impact to their sales from promotions. Lucky Charms, Cocoa Puffs, and Cinnamon Toast Crunch see positive impacts to their sales that are both practically and statistically significant. Kix sees no statistically significant impact to its average sales, while Cheerios has a large negative impact that is also statistically significant.
